n-para.title: GENERAL
n-para.para: The function of this Illustrated Parts Catalog (IPC) is to give a list, with illustrations, of the assemblies and detail parts of the PW617F-E Turbofan Gas Turbine Engine, made by Pratt & Whitney Canada (P&WC). The standard for this publication is Engine Serial No. PCE-LC0001, Build Specification No. 1209.
This catalog is a supplement, not an alternative, to the related Engine Manual and the Cleaning, Inspection, Repair (CIR) Manual, which are the authority for the assembly and repair procedures.
This Illustrated Parts Catalog agrees with the instructions given in the Air Transport Association (ATA) Specification No. 2200.

The complete engine is equipped with an identification name plate which displays the manufacturer's name, engine model number, build specification number, engine serial number and other pertinent data.
The engine serial numbers are in a range that starts with PCE-LC0001.

Primary accessories which are not made by Pratt & Whitney Canada have their own nameplates which show the identification number, equipment serial number and other applicable data. These parts can also show a P&WC equivalent identification number.
The Technical Publications Department will welcome any suggestions for modification or improvement to this Illustrated Parts Catalog which will increase its usefulness.

unlitem.para: RSVP Customer Feedback Sheets are sent with new manuals and each subsequent revision. Please use these sheets to tell us about any errors or problems you find in this Illustrated Parts Catalog. To get more forms contact the Supervisor, Publications Customer Services Dept., at the address shown below. Send completed RSVP Customer Feedback Sheets to:

n-para.title: EFFECTIVITY AND BUILD SPECIFICATION
n-para.para: The Effectivity Code column, when used, shows the applicability of the parts to an engine model. A one-letter code identifies the engine parts which are used only for specified airframe installations.
The Build Specification number (BS No.) is the number assigned to an engine model for a particular customer application (aircraft installation).

n-para.title: REVISIONS
n-para.para: P&WC will revise this Illustrated Parts Catalog as necessary to include new approved data. Revised data is shown by a black bar in the left margin of text and illustration pages. Revised pages also have the date of the applicable revision in the bottom right corner.

n-para.title: SERVICE BULLETINS (SB)
n-para.para: Service Bulletins (SB) are supplied as necessary to give data or instructions to make modifications to the engine assemblies or parts. The changed part numbers given by an SB number will be included in this IPC at revisions. Refer to the Service Bulletin List for the full list of SBs included in this IPC.
The PW617F-E Service Bulletins have numbers with a PW600-72 prefix and are in the 65000 series (eg: PW600-72-65000).
Any reference to a Service Bulletin in this IPC is given with the P&WC in-house SB number (eg: SB65000) which is the last element of the ATA number.

n-para.title: DETAILED PARTS LIST
n-para.para: There is a Detailed Parts List for each section shown in the List of Chapter/Section/Subjects and there is a Table of Contents in front of each Detailed Parts List.
Each Detailed Parts List is divided into six columns, as follows:

The indention system used in this catalog shows how an assembly is related to the Next Higher Assembly (NHA). For a given item, the indention system shows the assembly or Group Descriptive Title in the farthest left position, and continues down into subsequent columns as follows:

Some parts are used to attach components or assemblies. These parts are identified by the term "ATTACHING PARTS " and they are at the same level of indention as the component or the assembly they attach. The symbol - - - - *- - - - follows the last item of the attaching parts to divide them from the subsequent component or assembly.

The quantity in the Units per Assembly column of the Detailed Parts List for each assembly is the total quantity used per engine at the location shown. The quantity for each detail part and/or subassembly indented below an assembly is the quantity used per assembly. Thus, the quantities specified are not always the total used per engine.

n-para.title: PART NUMBERING SYSTEM
n-para.para: The P&WC basic part number system uses seven-digit numbers from 3000000 thru 3119999-99. These basic part numbers can have letters and numbers to show which parts are available, in a range of classes and/or oversize/undersize dimensions, for selection during engine servicing and overhaul. You must use the full number on procurement documentation to make sure that the correct part is supplied. No special numbering system is used. Numbers are given to assemblies, subassemblies and details as necessary.

unlitem.para: Unless otherwise specified, the drawing revision letter at the end of a P&WC part number is not significant and it does not affect interchangeability.

n-para.para: Rework part numbers are shown in Service Bulletin sequence below the parts that can be reworked. These rework part numbers show the original part number with the prefix "##R" (e.g.: 01R31#####). The letters "RWK" are then shown in the Units per Assembly column. There are no item numbers for parts that are obtainable only by rework of other parts. This system shows the actual SB evolution of the engine configuration (i.e., the most recent configuration will have the latest alpha suffix to the item number).

Pratt and Whitney also gives part numbers to approved items, such as hardware (bolts, nuts, studs, etc.), to make a standard for these items. These numbers have the prefix "ST", four numbers, a dash and a suffix of two or three numbers (e.g.: ST3033-017). All the ST parts given with the same four numbers have the same shape and function, but their dimensions change with the different suffix numbers.

unlitem.para: Pratt and Whitney (P&W) is the only approved authority to give the ST part numbers in the 1000 range and the 2000 range. Pratt and Whitney Canada (P&WC) is the only approved authority to give the ST part numbers in the 3000 and the 5000 range.

n-para.para: P&WC uses its own part numbers to identify parts which come from suppliers. These part numbers can end with letters to agree with revisions to the basic supplier part number.You can purchase these parts directly from the supplier. The supplier part numbers are shown in the Part Number Column of the Detailed Parts List. The supplier codes and equivalent P&WC part numbers are shown in the Nomenclature column.

If there is a number in parentheses just below the part number, that number is the ATA number of the related part of the assembly. You can use that number to refer directly to the applicable section in the Engine Manual or in the Cleaning/Inspection/Repair Manual.
When ***** is printed in the PART NUMBER column: refer to the NOMENCLATURE column for instructions.

An Interchangeability Control (IC) part number is used to identify and to control the interchangeable parts which are approved for use on the engine. To identify these parts the words "Option (IC)" appear after the primary name in the Nomenclature column. The detail part numbers are then shown in the part number column under the option part number.

unlitem.para: Nut options are given in the . Refer to this table for the nut options shown in this IPC.
You must use the option (IC) part numbers to order parts. The supplier will supply the detail part which is available in his stock.

n-para.title: ITEM NUMBER
n-para.para: The Figure/Item column shows each figure number and gives the item numbers shown in that figure. The item numbers on the illustrations help the user to find a part in the Detailed Parts List. Where possible, the sequence of the illustrations and the Detailed Parts Lists follows the sequence of the engine disassembly procedures. If there is a dash (-) in front of an item number, this shows that this item is not shown on the illustration.

When a Service Bulletin (SB) revise a part, a new line is added for that part. This new line will have the same item number plus a letter (A thru Z, without the letters I and O) to show that it is a revised part.

n-para.title: HOW TO USE THIS CATALOG
n-para.para: The function of the Numerical Index is to help the user find the locations of all the engine parts and accessories shown in this IPC.

unlitem.para: The Numerical Index is divided into the Alpha section and the Numerical section. The Alpha section gives part numbers that begin with a letter and the Numerical section gives part numbers that begin with a number.

The Numerical Index gives all the P&WC and supplier part numbers found in the Detailed Part List. The Numerical Index refers to the Chapter/Section/Subject and the Figure where the part is shown. It also refers to the item number of that part in the figure, together with the necessary quantity.
The quantity given in the Total Required column is the total quantity necessary for a component or for an assembly.

n-para.para: A three-element Chapter/Section/Subject number is given to each engine section. This number is in the bottom right corner of each page above the page number. These numbers are given per the Air Transport Association (ATA) Specification No. 100.

unlitem.para: The first element of the number identifies the chapter. This Illustrated Parts Catalog contains data applicable to Chapters 72 thru 79. The second element identifies the engine section. Look in the list of Chapter/Section/Subjects for the different sections contained in this IPC.

para.refint: How to find a part when the part number is known (Ref. Figure 1):

unlitem.para: Look for the part number in the part number column of the Numerical Index. Read the chapter/section, figure and item numbers on the same line as the part number.
Go to the Detailed Parts List and find the chapter/section, figure and item number for that part.
Find the same item number on the related illustration. This shows the location of the part on the engine.

para.refint: How to find a part when the part number is not known (Ref. Figure 2):

unlitem.para: Look in 72-00-00 Figure 1 (Engine Assembly, Complete) of the Detailed Parts List and find the chapter/section and figure which is most applicable for the location of the part.
Go to that chapter/section and figure and find the part on the illustration. Read the item number for that part.
Look for the item number in the related Detailed Parts List to find the part number and name of the part.

n-para.title: CROSS-INDEX SYSTEMS
n-para.para: There are notes in the Nomenclature column which read "See Figure for NHA" or "See Figure for Breakdown". These refer to the applicable location where you can find more data about the specified part.

unlitem.para: The term “in sets” is used in this catalog to identify groups of parts that may be interchanged only as a complete set. Individual parts within the groups or sets may not be interchanged; they must be used as a set.

The term “interchangeable” is used to identify the interchangeability of the part in the Part Number column with the part indicated in the Nomenclature column. The interchangeability is allowed only within the model/installation effectivity code restrictions. The interchangeability is defined by a list of ATA 200 Part Replacement Codes (PRC) as follows:
The old part may be used to replace the old part only; the new part may be used to replace the old and new part.
Example: new part is functionally different from the old part to the extent that installation with the airframe is affected.
The old or new part may replace either the old or the new part.
Example: parts can be freely interchanged.
The old part must be replaced with the old part; the new part must be replaced with the new part.
Example: the new part will not fit where the old part was or vice-versa, i.e. incompatible interfaces.
When replacement comprises a set consisting of a quantity of a single part number (if replacement must be the full quantity used in one model/installation).
Example: blades, gears, or other parts which must be incorporated as a set.
All the old parts must be replaced by all the new parts as an assembly.

The term RESTRICTED INTERCHANGEABILITY WITH is used in this catalog to identify a part that is interchangeable only as specified in the applicable Service Bulletin. The Service Bulletin must be consulted to establish the interchangeability condition.
The word “DELETED” will appear in the part number column. If the part was deleted as a result of a SB activity, a “POST” reference to the SB will appear in the nomenclature column.
This term is used when a part is removed and no longer used as a result of SB activity or that the part was listed in the IPC by error and that it is not applicable to this engine model.
A highlights page will be added to the cover sheet for IPC revisions to indicate which part number has been removed.
For the relocation of a part to a different chapter/section/subject or figure. The nomenclature column will indicate what or where to find the part number.

This term is used to advise of the latest approved revision level of a supplier part number that does not require a P&WC part number change. Changes done by the supplier of the component, which do not affect the form, fit and function of the component, are recorded through a revision level that can be of a dash number (e.g., -1), revision letter (e.g., A) or a combination of a letter and number (e.g., L1). The latest revision level is TWO-WAY INTERCHANGEABLE with all prior revisions of the same Fig. Item Part Number.

This term is used in the Units per Assembly column to advise that the part can only be obtained through rework. The rework number will not be assigned an item number; they will be incorporated after the "family" number (the saleable number from which they are a rework of). The nomenclature will always be followed with the term "Reworked from".
